THE WAY I/WE NEED THIS BOOK.

Following @thenapministry on Instagram helped me BEGIN to recognize some of the sneaky ways systemic oppression lived within me through the expectations I put on myself to produce, work and provide for others, keeping myself pretty low on the priority list, ultimately leading to my very very very intense burnout.

At first, I shamed myself for burning out. Then, I became annoyed that a day off, a weekend off, a week off, a month off-ish, all weren't enough to get out of burn-out.

And now, I meet my feelings of burnout with real tender love. Like meeting a younger and too-long-neglected part of me. Allowing her to need my care and attention for as long as she needs.

This book arrived into my hands today. It feels like a cheerleader, greeting me at the halfway mark of a marathon, giving me the boost of energy I need to KEEP RESTING and KEEP RESISTING the false beliefs that drain my energy.

Wishing all of you deep rest in the final month of yet another challenging year.

Take a damn nap. Our collective liberation needs you too.

I just found a journal from 2010. I have so many feelings and thoughts about this cloud doodle and quoted conversation. My way of pointing at toxic positivity or bypassing before I knew about the terms. Peace, both inner and collective, is hard hard hard work that requires us to look at the shadows and still believe that believing beyond despair is valuable/possible.

Kinda funny to see that my present day work has been steeping from tiiiiiiiiiiime. Sometimes I'm made to believe that my work focus now came out of nowhere, but stumbling across this reminds me that it's in my essence.

INTRODUCING JEN MARAMBA //

It's a real big honour to be collaborating with @jenmaramba for our Mindfulness, Movement and Creative Expression workshop @at_theagh on March 8, 7-9pm alongside me (@royolaroyola).

I've been lucky enough to know Jen for over a decade and the gift of her presence and connection have been major turning points in my life, healing and expression.

Here's more about Jen and why next Wednesday is going to be BIG MAGIC!

🌟✨💥💫🌟
Jen Maramba / Tulay Araw (She/her/siya) sits upon and honours the land of the Anishinabewaki ᐊᓂᔑᓈᐯᐗᑭ & the Mississaugas of the Credit First Nation and continues to learn and embody teachings to share the land peacefully while aligning with Indigenous sovereignty that allows All beings to a thrive. Jen honours her most recent ancestral lineage of Pangasinan and Panay Island, from the islands commonly known through the colonial name of the Philippines. 

Jen is a mother, healer & artist in Tkaronto (Toronto) / Guelph, Canada. Her gifted name from her elders, Tulay Araw,  means the Sun Bridge. Jen co-directs the Kapwa Collective group’s creative and collaborative projects that disseminate Filipino Indigenous Knowledge Systems and Practices locally with local elders from communities to bridge narratives and teachings with the intention of acknowledging her own identity as a visitor and what it means to be 'Filipin@/x' - 'Canadian'.

Jen is an interdisciplinary artist and creative arts facilitator/educator promoting healing through art. As an artist and healer, Jen has developed and facilitated arts healing for Tkaronto (Toronto, Canada) community groups, organizations and individuals. Her current creative practice allows for individuals and groups to explore the healing power of nature and community with nature through a creative process of visual art, sound art, dialogical art and movement. Jen is a movement guide, Hilot / healing touch practitioner, and sacred space holder.

Jen holds Sacred Circles and ceremonies for BIPOC Healers and individuals who need a loving and safe place to hold Ritual and Ceremony for sacred intention, release, healing and to connect with Ancestors and Guides.

From their Filipinx performance art beginnings over a decade ago, today's the day that @jenmaramba and @royolaroyola reunite in collaboration @at_theagh for movement, mindfulness and creative expression.

Tune into your body and its inherent creativity. Move, mark make, witness your own wisdom.

GOOD GRIEF //

1 yr ago I (Robin) made the very hard decision to close the physical studio. I was (still am) too burntout and under-resourced to keep the physical space alive and continue working the way the space seemed to demand of me. My mental, emotional and physical well-being required me to let it go.

The aftermath of closing the space continues to impact not only me, but many. For a multitude of reasons. But I'm gonna share the most painful reason for me here:

Many racialized folks walk around with lots of armour to repel minutely microaggressions and macro aggressions as we endeavor to survive and thrive in this world. GBF was a space where we could take our armour off or at least loosen it a bit.

Since closing, I'm remembering anew how tiring it is to wear all this armour. Now that GBF classes are offered in other spaces, our teachers are experiencing increased exposure to "undercover" racism. 

So I grieve. And hope others can rally to create safer and intentional spaces where Black folks, Indigenous folks, racialized folks, queer folks, disabled folks, fat folks, +++ can feel welcomed to be in their body and in community.

This thread features words from @clairitytarot posted in their stories today. And a snapshot from GBFs first BIPGM exclusive workshop in Feb 2019 when we first opened.

I dream of gatherings like this again, so that feelings like Clair shared are prevented or released/soothed/met.

Please be kind. We are sad today.

TOMORROW⚡️IRL movement @at_theagh 

Join us for a mixed modality class blending strength, freedom, nervous system regulation, and flow. @jamiilcorin will be teaching the next two weeks for @clairitytarot. 

Sign up via the link in our bio!

NEW IN PERSON WORKSHOP with @_soulfuel hosted at @move.room.hamont ! 

BODY LANGUAGE // An embodied movement and somatic dance exploration for BIPGM (Black, Indigenous,  people of the global majority) and queer folks.

This workshop is a safer space for BIPGM / queer folks to exist in their bodies together and explore their embodied healing through mindful movement and free-form dance.

No experience needed.

This exploration will be guided with cues rooted in trauma awareness. the intention is to inspire folks to move intuitively by attuning to their emotional and somatic intelligence.

Be ready to sweat (maybe cry and celebrate too.)

Invitations // Bring journal, wear breathable clothing and/or something that allows you to feel comfortable and empowered in your style.

Sliding scale $10-25

This week we have two in-person class offerings, both starring @jamiilcorin!

Wednesday @at_theagh at 7pm (6:30pm gallery tour included in your ticket!)

Saturday @hamiltonlibrary (Central Library) at 11am FREE!

Registration links are in our bio.

Ja'miil has such a sweetness to their teaching, bringing that accessible fire, killer playlist and playful energy that invites you to enjoyyyyyyy your body and the shapes it can make.

The body’s language is our first language, yet more often than not, we don’t prioritize listening to it, or even know how to.

In this workshop, Lor will guide us through a gentle embodiment journey, where we’ll practice and refine our relationship with ourselves.

We’ll find ways to cultivate senses of safety, peace and joy. Rest our minds by moving intentionally and staying present with our breath. Restore our energy by surrendering to our authentic expression. Embody our agency and gift ourselves with gestures that feel nourishing.

Body Language is simply an opportunity to meet ourselves with compassionate awareness and respond with our presence.

Join us on Saturday April 29th. Tickets available in bio ✨

YOU ARE LOVED AND YOUR SAFETY IS PARAMOUNT.

To folks impacted by today's protest and counter protests we're here for you.

My nervous system is still reeling from witnessing the hate and aggression at the protests outside of HWDSB headquarters. Our queer chants stayed firm in love ethic. Our love and advocacy was met with bullying behaviours, with teens/tweens/kids instigating violence. 

If you're feeling feelings too, I want to support you.

Email (hello@goodbodyfeel.com) for free access to the GBF movement library.

Reach out to @speqtrumyhm, they're hosting a gathering on Friday Sep 22 for trans and gender diverse folks to process and coregulate. And an education session for any and all folks on Mon Sep 25.

Sending so much peace peace peace.
Love, not hate.
